    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-09-13T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-09-13T18:00:00-05:00" n="586"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d586">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">394.31/9–1351: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Italy</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-09-13T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 13, 1951—7 p. m</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1213. Urtel 1158.<note n="1" xml:id="d586fn1">Dated September 10, <ref
                            target="#pg_1403">p. 1403</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>1. See Para 3(2) and (3) <gloss target="#t_Depcirtel1">Depcirtel</gloss> Sept 12
                    re Ital fear Czech reprisals and status approaches other Govts.</p>
                <p>2. US chose Art XXV in preference XXIII as making unnecessary <gloss
                        target="#t_CP1">CP</gloss>s discuss merits US and Czech action, thus
                    relieving other <gloss target="#t_CP1">CP</gloss>s necessity taking sides or
                    taking parallel action as wd be neces if we proved cases Czech nullification and
                    impairment. Uncertain also whether <gloss target="#t_CP1">CP</gloss>s wd agree
                    complete nullification by Czecho exists with result difficult obtain
                    authorization terminate all our obligations <pb facs="1425" n="1409"
                        xml:id="pg_1409"/> Czecho. XXIII wd also involve making case against
                    state-trading operations which might be interpreted as attack on state trading
                    as such and hence antagonize other <gloss target="#t_CP1">CP</gloss>s.</p>
                <p>3. Unwilling use Art XXI as bad precedent opening way to unlimited use that Art
                    for actions having far less relation to security than Czech case.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
